1.) Introduction

¶

The housing market has plenty of factors that keep the numbers changing for home sales, including seasonality. Past data shows that sales activity increase during the warmer months. We want to find out, given a particular type of house, is there anything that can make it look more appealing during different seasons? We understand there exist a variety of house types, but there are still a finite number of house amenities. We shall take a look at a sample of these features in attempts to seek a correlation between the timing and pricing of the house sold. Specifically, we want to find out what type of features make a house more valuable during certain seasons. We will focus on three amenities: fireplaces, porches/decks,and garage type. To achieve our goal, we plan to use all the skills we aquired over the semester in working with python, pandas, matplotlib, and more to analyze a dataset of home sales data.

Overall, we believe that our analysis will provide valuable insights into the correlation between home sales and seasons, and help us understand which amenities are most valuable in different seasons. We hope that our findings will be useful for homeowners and real estate agents looking to optimize the sale of their homes.

Our null hypothesis suggests that there is no relationship between the number of houses sold during a particular season and the type of amenities of the house.

2.) Data Wrangling


2.A.) Meeting the Data


The dataset of house sales we took is from Ames, Iowa. This dataset contains over 80 columns and needs to be reduced in order to target our focus only on relevant data. The first step would be to import the data for use and to drop any columns that are not related to home amenities. In order to build an effective model, we will need to make sure we identify and work with only relevant columns.

3.) Porch & Deck Correlations

¶

3.A.) Linear Regression regarding Decks and Porches


The first feature we investigate are the porches and decks. These plots show the relationship between the sale price vs the area of the porches. We first filter the data to only include houses that have a non-zero area for the respective porch type, in order to exclude houses without a porch and avoid bias. Then, we use the scikit-learn library's LinearRegression class to fit a linear regression model to the data for each porch type. The resulting model is then used to generate predictions for porch area values between the minimum and maximum observed values. Finally, we print the slope of the fitted regression lines, and create scatter plots of the observed data with the fitted regression lines overlaid.

In [6]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

wood = house_df.query('WoodDeckSF != 0')
porch = house_df.query('OpenPorchSF != 0')

X_wood = wood['WoodDeckSF'].values.reshape(-1,1)
X_porch = porch['OpenPorchSF'].values.reshape(-1,1)
Y_w = wood['SalePrice'].values
Y_p = porch['SalePrice'].values

reg = LinearRegression()
reg2 = LinearRegression()

prediction_wood = np.linspace(min(X_wood), max(X_wood)).reshape(-1, 1)
prediction_porch = np.linspace(min(X_porch), max(X_porch)).reshape(-1, 1)

reg.fit(X_wood, Y_w)
reg2.fit(X_porch, Y_p)

wood_pred = reg.predict(prediction_wood)
porch_pred = reg2.predict(prediction_porch)
print('Slope for Wood Deck Area vs House Price Regression: %f'%reg.coef_[0])
print('Slope for Open Porch Area vs House Price Regression: %f'%reg2.coef_[0])

wood.plot.scatter('WoodDeckSF','SalePrice', color= 'b')
plt.plot(prediction_wood, wood_pred, color='red', linewidth=3)
plt.title("Wood Deck Square Feet vs Sale Price")
plt.xlabel('Wood Deck Area in Square Feet')
plt.ylabel('House Sale Price')
porch.plot.scatter('OpenPorchSF','SalePrice', color= 'b')
plt.plot(prediction_porch, porch_pred, color='red', linewidth=3)
plt.title("Porch Square Feet vs Month Sold")
plt.xlabel("Open porch Area in Square Feet")
plt.show()

Slope for Wood Deck Area vs House Price Regression: 149.854728
Slope for Open Porch Area vs House Price Regression: 106.935459

3.A.) Open Porches vs Wooden Deck Summary

¶

With some notable exceptions, we see that the data is skewed towards having a lower average porch area, with a lower general sales price. We can also notice that on average wooden decks have more square area than an open porch. This correlates to the regression lines generated because the slope for wooden deck area vs price is slightly higher than the slope from open porch area vs price. The regression lines generated have a very small increasing slope, but yet still shows that as the porch area increases so does the price of the house.

Based on this information, it is hard to say if having an open porch vs a wooden deck has any more influence on the price of the house by itself. But it is fairly likely that houses with larger porches will have a higher sale price. Additionally, since the data shows that the relationship between open porch area and sale price is weak, it may prove more useful to focus on seasonal purchasing trends.

3.B.) Comparing Types of Porches with Month Sold

¶

The purpose of this code is to create scatter plots of three different porch areas (enclosed, screened, and 3-season) versus the month in which the house was sold. The data is filtered to only include houses that have a non-zero area for the respective porch type, and the resulting data is plotted using matplotlib's scatter() function. The color of each plotted point corresponds to the porch type (enclosed porches are red, screened porches are blue, and 3-season porches are green).

Text(0, 0.5, 'Area in Square Feet')

3.B.) Summary

¶

These plots differ dramatically and have very different trends and correlations. When looking at the distribution of enclosed porch area versus the month sold, we can see that it starts out with a very steady upwards trend until July, at which point there is a sudden drop in the porch square footage that is included with houses that are sold. This may indicate that buyers are less interested in houses with enclosed porches during the end of summer months, or that the supply of such houses is lower at that time. Further analysis would be needed to determine the exact cause of this trend.

The next plot would be for screened porch area (Blue). We can tell right off the bat that these type of houses are less in quantity, thus we see that the scatterplot data is more sparse for this type of porch. You can work out a very slight increasing trend amoung the amount of square footage of porch a house is sold with. Just like with the enclosed porch area, we see a huge spike in sales in the summer months of June and July, but this time the datapoints are mainly outliers as we see the majority of the large screened porches (>300 Square Feet) being sold.

Lastly, we see that the three season porch plot is even more sparse then the screened porches before it. This makes it very difficult to see if a 3 season porch has any correlation with month at all. More data of houses with 3 season porch sales will be needed to say something about it's trend. Still, it is interesting to see that the outliers for large seasonal porches only exist during the warmer months where having a nice porch is more desirable.

4.) Porch Type Distributions


4.A.) Enclosed Porche Area VS Month Sold


We would like to better examine the trend of the porch area a house has vs the month it was sold. We can accomplish this by making a violin plot of each.

4.A.) Summary

¶

We see that the average of each month stays relatively steady with small peaks and valleys up until about July which is the exact same trend that we saw in the scatter plot in 3B, thus confirming our intuition about that trend to be accurate. Within this January to June time frame we also can look at the distribution of porch area per month. It is obvious that January had a very 'bottom-heavy' distribution where the most houses were sold with low porch area compared to any month. However, this bottom heavy distribution seems to fade after Febuary leading to March which has a very skinny distribution. This can be equated to the obvious outlier (or outliers) that the month had. we see that the distribution seems get back to the way it was in April and then we get to the summer months which all have a more symmetric distribution, but still a very similar average. After the summer months we see a dip in sales with greater (> ~100 Square Feet) square footage of porches with a sudden increase in November. This month we see that there is a 'top-heavy' distribution with the greatest average out of every month. Then we see our lowest average porch area sold around December. The trend so far is that summer months generally see the most consistent porch sales, while other months have more of an unpredictible distribution.

5.) FirePlace Correlation Data


5.A.) Mean Sales Prices by Fireplace and Month Sold


Moving on, we want to see if there is some sort of correlation with the number of fireplaces a house is sold with within a given month versus the sale price of the house. Specifically, we would like to focus on any correlation that shows up relating to fireplace sales in the winter months.

In [11]:
## Group the data by the 'Fireplace' column and the 'MoSold' column
grouped_data = house_df.groupby(['Fireplaces', 'MoSold'])

## Calculate the mean sales price for each group
mean_sales_price = grouped_data['SalePrice'].mean()
In [12]:
## Unstack the grouped data to create a DataFrame with one column per 'Fireplace' value
unstacked_data = mean_sales_price.unstack(level=0)
unstacked_data.sort_values(by=['MoSold'], key = month, inplace=True) 
## NOTE: This call is static and cannot be ran twice without errors
In [13]:
## Plot the resulting DataFrame using a bar chart
unstacked_data.plot(kind='bar', width=0.8)
plt.title("Mean Sales Prices by Fireplace and Month Sold")
plt.xlabel("Month Sold")
plt.ylabel("Sales Price")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.149,1.017))
plt.show()

5.A.) Summary

¶

Overall, we see that there is an obvious correlation between a higher house sale price and having 1 or more fire places. Most houses with 2 fireplaces on average sold for more in the months of January, March, and April. However, our prediction that houses with more fireplaces would have a higher sale price in the winter season was not necessarily correct, as September, October, November, and December all had relatively low sale prices for houses with 2 fireplaces. There is a trend with houses that have a single fireplace, with high prices in January decreasing into March, April, and May before bottoming out in June, then rising in July and averaging out for the winter seasons.

6.) The Garage Trials


6.A.) Trends in Garage Types VS Month of Sale


In [15]:
X = ['Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','June','July','Aug','Sept','Oct','Nov','Dec']
det = []
att = []
for i in range(0,12):
    month = house_df.loc[house_df['MoSold'] == X[i]]
    month_att = month['GarageType'].value_counts()['Attchd']
    month_det = month['GarageType'].value_counts()['Detchd']
    att.append(month_att)
    det.append(month_det)

   
br1 = np.arange(len(X))
br2 = [X + 0.25 for X in br1]
plt.bar(X,att,color='blue', width = 0.25,
        edgecolor ='grey', label ='Attached')
plt.bar(br2,det, color='red', width = 0.25,
        edgecolor ='grey', label ='Detached')
plt.legend()
plt.title("Number of Garage Types vs Month Sold")
plt.xlabel('Month Sold')
plt.ylabel('Number of Garage Type Sold')
plt.show()

6.A.) Summary

¶

Here we see an obvious normal distribution from both attached and detached garage types with an ever so slight left tail. The number of sales for homes with attached garages steadily rise from January through June, where they peak and then take a sudden and drastic decline which continues until September. This general trend follows for detached garage sales as well. At this point there does seem to be more evidence of a possible correlation with most ammentities and the summer season rather than the winter season which should be examined further.

7.) Cold Yet?


7.A.) Number of Houses Sold by Heating/Cooling Quality and Month


Here we can set out to see if there is a correlation with AC quality and purchases in the winter season versus the summer season.

In [16]:
barWidth = 0.25
ex = []
gd = []
ta = []
fa = []
po = []

for i in range(0,12):
    month = house_df.loc[house_df['MoSold'] == X[i]]
    if 'Ex' in month.values:
        E = month['HeatingQC'].value_counts()['Ex']
        ex.append(E)
    else:
        ex.append(0)
        
    if 'Gd' in month['HeatingQC'].values:
        G = month['HeatingQC'].value_counts()['Gd']
        gd.append(G)
    else:
        gd.append(0)
        
    if 'Fa' in month['HeatingQC'].values:
        F = month['HeatingQC'].value_counts()['Fa']
        fa.append(F)
    else:
        fa.append(0)
        
    if 'TA' in month['HeatingQC'].values:
        T = month['HeatingQC'].value_counts()['TA']
        ta.append(T)
    else:
        ta.append(0)
        
    if 'Po' in month['HeatingQC'].values:
        P = month['HeatingQC'].value_counts()['Po']
        po.append(P)
    else:
        po.append(0)

br1 = np.arange(len(X))
br2 = [X + barWidth for X in br1]
br3 = [X + barWidth for X in br2]
br4 = [X + barWidth for X in br3]
br5 = [X + barWidth for X in br4]

plt.bar(X,ex,color='blue', width = barWidth,
        edgecolor ='grey', label ='Excellent')
plt.bar(br2,gd, color='red', width = barWidth,
        edgecolor ='grey', label ='Good')
plt.bar(br3,ta, color='green', width = barWidth,
        edgecolor ='grey', label ='Typical')
plt.bar(br4,fa, color='purple', width = barWidth,

plt.xlabel('Month Sold')
plt.ylabel('Number of AC Quality Type Sold')

7.A.) Summary

¶

Here there is an absolutely staggering resemblance in distribution compared to the garage sale quantities vs month sold distribution above. Not only that, but all AC Quality types seem to have the exact same general distribution (except for the 'poor' quality type since the dataset has very little homes that have poor AC). This lack of a trend between AC quality types is shown through a matched normal distribution of what the house sales already looked like during a typical year. A second identical distribution showing the same general trend of more sales in the summer for all measurements of a fireplace, leads us to believe that there may not be a correlation between the home features and the timing of the sale after all.

8.) Proving/Disproving the Null


8.A.) Fitting a Linear Regression Model for Month VS All Amenities


We want to set up a models where the dependent variables resembles the month that house was sold while using ALL the amenities examined above as the independent variables.

In [17]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()
# Fit the encoder to the MoSold column and transform the values to be numeric
house_df['MoSold_num'] = le.fit_transform(house_df['MoSold'])
formula = 'MoSold_num ~ HeatingQC + Fireplaces + GarageType + WoodDeckSF + OpenPorchSF + SeasonalPorch + ScreenPorch + EnclosedPorch'
# fit the model to the data
model = smf.ols(formula, data=house_df).fit()
print(model.summary())

8.A.) Summary

¶

Based on the p-values in the statistical summary, it seems that most of the features in the model do not have a significant effect on the dependent variable. The two exceptions are Fair Heating Quality and Seasonal Porches, which have p-values less than 0.05 and therefore show stronger statistical evidence against the null hypothesis. However these data columns only have a small number of datapoints, which may not be enough to reliably conclude that they have a significant effect on the dependent variable.

10.) Conclusion

¶

Based on our analysis of data from 2006 to 2010, we found that there were only some weak correlations between some amenities and summer seasons, but not for winter seasons. One factor that could have influenced these trends is the 2008 market crash, which was a major economic recession that had a significant impact on the housing market. Since our data only spans over a short time period, it may be possible that the relationships between house amenities and seasonal sales differ outside this time frame and in different geographic regions. Another factor influencing the lack of correlation could simply be that the majority of house buyers have higher priorities when looking for a house, more important to them than the amendities.

Looking at our data plots, we can notice that different types of a certain house feature follow the distributions the same. This is a sign that no type of amentity has a significantly powerful influence in the housing market based on this data. The first signs of this was shown in our figures plotting the house sale price against the amentity types. In these figures we saw very small positive slopes and evenly leveled distributions that show no trends. For example, when graphing the number of fireplaces by the sale price of the house, we see that for each bar color the slope remains fairly constant with very few exceptions. With little evidence of a trend, we can not reasonably prove our hypothesis to be correct. Also the p-values generated using Ordinary Least Squares only showed 2 values that were less than 0.05, and these were the amentity types that had insufficient data. Therefore, with the absence of any relevant p-value less than 0.05, we must fail to reject our null hypothesis.
